nnale of Israeli Ceramics\u201c, 1 Aug. 2016 \u2013 10 Nov. 2016. Ariel Berliski\u2019s \u201c'''Mute Nature'''\u201d from the Levin Collection was displayed in the framework of the exhibition.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Riba |first1=Naama |title=Breasts With Gaping Mouths and Frozen Embryos: Israeli Ceramics Biennale Pushes Limits of Clay |url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/culture/.premium.MAGAZINE-breasts-with-gaping-mouths-at-israeli-ceramics-biennale-1.5456943 |work=Haaretz}}</ref> \n\n\u2022 Mishkan Museum of Art, Ein Haron, \u201cAliza Auerbach \u2013 Life\u201d, Oct.-Dec. 2016.\n\n\u2022 The Israel Museum, Jerusalem, \u201cBehold the Man: Jesus in Israeli Art\u201d, 22 Dec. 2016 \u2013 18 Apr. 2017. Joseph Budko\u2019s: \u201c'''The Wandering Jew'''\u201d and \u201c'''The Crucified'''\u201d from the Levin Collection were displayed in the framework of the exhibition.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Steinberg |first1=Jessica |title=At Israel Museum exhibit, Jesus comes back to the Jews |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/at-israel-museum-exhibit-jesus-comes-back-to-the-jews/ |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=The Times of Israel |date=23 January 2017}}</ref> \n\n\u2022 Benaki Museum, Greece, \u201cRoee Rosen \u2013 Live and Die as Eva Brown\u201d, 8 Apr. 2016 \u2013 16 July. 2017\n\n\u2022 Gordon Gallery, \u201cAmir Shefet \u2013 Starheartbutterflyrainbow\u201d, 3 Sep. 2015 \u2013 3 Oct. 2015.\n\n\u2022 Herzliya Museum of Contemporary Art, \u201cUri Lifshitz: Flesh and Blood\u201d, 28 May. 2016 \u2013 3 Sep. 2016. The piece \u201c'''Looking in the mirror'''\u201d from the Levin Collection was displayed in the framework of the exhibition.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Yahav |first1=Galia |title=The Artist Who Represented Violent Israeli Masculinity |url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/culture/.premium.MAGAZINE-violent-sensual-unapologetic-1.5404329 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=Haaretz |date= 2 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n\u2022 Tel Aviv Museum of Art, \u201cLeonid Balaklav: An Obsessive Portraitist\u201d, 24 Jun. 2015 \u2013 10 Oct. 2015. The painting \u201c'''Portrait of Gideon Ofrat'''\u201d from the Levin Collection was displayed in the framework of the exhibition.<ref>{{cite news |title=Leonid Balaklav: An Obsessive Portraitist |url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/event/20150616-leonid-balaklav |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=BBC-Culture}}</ref>\n \n\u2022 Man\u00e9-Katz Museum, Haifa, \u201cThe Jewish Avant-Garde Modigliani, Lipchitz, Zadkine and others\u201d, 14 Dec. 2014 \u2013 28 Jul. 2015. The following paintings from the Levin collection were displayed in the framework of the exhibition: \u201c'''The Prophet in the Desert'''\u201d (Reuven Rubin), \u201c'''Seated Arab'''\u201d (Joseph Constant), \u201c'''Hora'''\u201d (Moshe Matusowski), \u201c'''Family in the Diaspora'''\u201d (Reuven Rubin)\n\n== Sponsoring Catalogues ==\n   \n\u2022 '''All in the Family: Family Legacy in Israeli Art''', ed. Prof. Haim Maor, Beer Sheva: Ben Gurion University of the Negev \u2013 Department of the Arts, 2018 [Hebrew]\n\n\u2022 '''New Barbizon: Back to Life''', ed. Yaniv Shapira, En Harod: Mishkan Museum of Art, 2017 [Hebrew]\n\n\u2022 '''Aliza Auerbach: Life''', ed. Aliza Auerbach, Guy Raz, En Harod: Mishkan Museum of Art, 2016 [Hebrew]\n\n\u2022 '''Starheartbutterflyrainbow''', Gordon Gallery, 2015 [Hebrew]\n\n== Selected Books and Catalogues ==\n\n\u2022 '''Broad Horizons: 120 Years of Israeli Art - from the Ofrat Collection to the Levin Collection''', author and editor: Gideon Ofrat, Jerusalem: Levin Press, 2013 [Hebrew and English]\n\n\u2022 '''Broader Horizons: 120 Years of Israeli Art \u2013 from the Ofrat Collection to the Levin Collection''', author and editor: Gideon Ofrat, Jerusalem: Levin Press, 2014 [Hebrew and English]\n\n\u2022 '''Berlin-Jerusalem: The Art of the German Immigration''', author and editor: Gideon Ofrat, Tel Aviv: Levin Press, 2015 [Hebrew]\n\n\u2022 '''Paris-Tel Aviv: the French Connection of Israeli Art''', author and editor: Gideon Ofrat, Tel Aviv: Levin Press, 2015 [Hebrew]\n\n\u2022 '''New York-Tel Aviv: the American Connection of Israeli Art''', author and editor: Gideon Ofrat, Tel Aviv: Levin Press, 2016 [Hebrew]\n\n\u2022 '''Jerusalem \u2013 Tel Aviv: Art in Urban Conflict''', editor: Gideon Ofrat, Tel Aviv: Institute for Israeli Art at the Academic College of Tel Aviv-Yafo, 2016 [Hebrew]\n\n\u2022 '''Beyond the Horizon: 120 Years of Israeli Art \u2013 from the Ofrat Collection to the Levin Collection''', author and editor: Gideon Ofrat, Jerusalem: Levin Press, 2017 [Hebrew and English]\n\n\u2022 '''Ludwig Blum: 1948''', author and editor: Gideon Ofrat, Tel Aviv: Levin Press, 2018 [Hebrew and English]\n\n\u2022 '''Yuval Shaul: Violence & Compassion''', Tel Aviv: Levin Press, 2018 [Hebrew]\n\n\u2022 '''Igael Tumarkin''', author: Gideon Ofrat, Tel Aviv: Levin Press, 2019 [Hebrew]\n\n== External Links ==\nLevin Art Community & Culture's [https://www.levinartandculture.com/ Official Website] [Hebrew]'\n\n== Notes and References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (6)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Levin_Art_Community_%26_Culture"}
{"title_page": "Thor Kunkel", "text_new": "[[File:ThorKunkel.jpg|thumb|Thor Kunkel (2013)]]\n'''Thor Kunkel''', a German author, was born in [[Frankfurt am Main]] on 2 September 1963. Kunkel claims to have spent his youth associating with drug friends and American soldiers stationed in the then [[West Germany]]. In 1981, on a scholarship to the United States, he enrolled in the creative writing programme of the [[San Francisco Art Institute]].\n\nFollowing his return to West Germany, Kunkel joined the staff of advertising agency [[Young & Rubicam]], then in 1988 joined the Swiss [[GGK (advertising agency)|GGK]] in [[London, England]].  After marrying Dutch artist Gerda Bakker, he moved to [[Amsterdam]] in 1992 and re-joined Young & Rubicam as creative director, quitting in 1996 to take up directing and writing.  He now lives in Switzerland and the Netherlands.  His first novel, ''The Blacklight-Terrarium'' (1999), won him a major German literary prize.{{citation needed|date=April 2010}} His 2011 novel ''Subs'' will be put into a film with [[Subs (film)|the same title]] by director [[Oskar Roehler]].<ref>http://www.cicero.de/salon/film-roman-subs-regisseur-oskar-roehler-autor-thor-kunkel-interview/56347</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''Das Schwarzlicht-Terrarium'' (2000) {{ISBN|3-499-22646-4}}\n* ''Ein Brief an Hanny Porter'' (2000) {{ISBN|3-499-22678-2}}\n* ''[[Endstufe (novel)|Endstufe]]'' (2004) {{ISBN|3-8218-0753-9}}\n* ''Kuhls Kosmos'' (2008) {{ISBN|3-927734-41-1}}\n* ''Schaumschwester'' (2010) {{ISBN|3-88221-690-5}}\n* ''Subs'' (2011) {{ISBN|3453266927}}\n* ''Wanderful - Mein neues Leben in den Bergen'', Eichborn-Verlag, K\u00f6ln, 2014 {{ISBN|978-3-8479-0568-4}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://thor-kunkel.com/ Official website]\n*[http://www.3ammagazine.com/litarchives/2005/jan/interview_thor_kunkel.html Interview with 3:AM Magazine]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kunkel, Thor}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:German male novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male writers]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:ThorKunkel.jpg|thumb|Thor Kunkel (2013)]]\n'''Thor Kunkel''', a German author, was born in [[Frankfurt am Main]] on 2 September 1963. Kunkel claims to have spent his youth associating with drug friends and American soldiers stationed in the then [[West Germany]]. In 1981, on a scholarship to the United States, he enrolled in the creative writing programme of the [[San Francisco Art Institute]].\n\nFollowing his return to West Germany, Kunkel joined the staff of advertising agency [[Young & Rubicam]], then in 1988 joined the Swiss [[GGK (advertising agency)|GGK]] in [[London, England]].  After marrying Dutch artist Gerda Bakker, he moved to [[Amsterdam]] in 1992 and re-joined Young & Rubicam as creative director, quitting in 1996 to take up directing and writing.  He now lives in Switzerland and the Netherlands.  His first novel, ''The Blacklight-Terrarium'' (1999), won him a major German literary prize.{{citation needed|date=April 2010}} His 2011 novel ''Subs'' will be put into a film with [[Subs (film)|the same title]] by director [[Oskar Roehler]].<ref>http://www.cicero.de/salon/film-roman-subs-regisseur-oskar-roehler-autor-thor-kunkel-interview/56347</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''Das Schwarzlicht-Terrarium'' (2000) {{ISBN|3-499-22646-4}}\n* ''Ein Brief an Hanny Porter'' (2000) {{ISBN|3-499-22678-2}}\n* ''[[Endstufe (novel)|Endstufe]]'' (2004) {{ISBN|3-8218-0753-9}}\n* ''Kuhls Kosmos'' (2008) {{ISBN|3-927734-41-1}}\n* ''Schaumschwester'' (2010) {{ISBN|3-88221-690-5}}\n* ''Subs'' (2011) {{ISBN|3453266927}}\n* ''Wanderful - Mein neues Leben in den Bergen'', Eichborn-Verlag, K\u00f6ln, 2014 {{ISBN|978-3-8479-0568-4}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://thor-kunkel.com/ Official website]\n*[http://www.3ammagazine.com/litarchives/2005/jan/interview_thor_kunkel.html Interview with 3:AM Magazine]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kunkel, Thor}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century German novelists]]\n[[Category:German male novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thor_Kunkel"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Wensing", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image = \n| name          = Thomas Wensing\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1978|05|01}}\n| birth_place   = [[Cologne]], [[Germany]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = German\n| othername     = \n| spouse        = \n| yearsactive   = 1999\u2013present\n| occupation    = Writer and poet\n| website       = [http://www.wortgewebe.de/ Official website of Thomas Wensing] {{in lang|de}}\n}}\n'''Thomas Wensing''' (born May 1, 1978 in [[Cologne]]) is a German [[author]] of poetry and short stories.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=_DS3oAEACAAJ&dq=K%C3%BCrschners+Deutscher+Literatur-Kalender+2014&hl=de&sa=X&ei=z9MFVKfjKrKM4gSRuoGgCQ&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAA ''Thomas Wensing.''] In: ''[[K\u00fcrschners Deutscher Literatur-Kalender]] 2014/2015: Band I: A-O. Band II: P-Z.'', Walter De Gruyter Incorporated, 2014, P. 1132, {{ISBN|978-3-11-033720-4}}.</ref>\n\n== Life and works ==\nThomas Wensing, born 1978 in Cologne ([[North Rhine-Westphalia]]) has studied at the [[University of Cologne]] and at the [[Catholic University of Eichst\u00e4tt-Ingolstadt]].<ref>Biographical details of ''Thomas Wensing.'' In: ''Mitschrift.'', Martin Werhand Verlag, 2014, P. 169</ref> He obtained his PhD from the latter institution in 2011.<ref>[http://www.ku.de/wwf/pw/forschung/inventory-management/optimization-of-periodically-reviewed-inventory-systems/ Thomas Wensing at ''Catholic University of Eichst\u00e4tt-Ingolstadt''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150519060254/http://www.ku.de/wwf/pw/forschung/inventory-management/optimization-of-periodically-reviewed-inventory-systems/ |date=May 19, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nBesides studies and occupation, Wensing developed skills in writing literary texts.<ref>Biographical Data of ''Thomas Wensing.'' In: ''Zwischenspiel (Short Stories).'', Martin Werhand Verlag, 2015, P. 233</ref> Since the late 1990s, he has been publishing poetry in a couple of anthologies, e.g. in ''Junge Lyrik'',<ref>[http://www.ksta.de/junge-zeiten/junge-lyrik,16129136,14033596.html ''K\u00f6lner Stadt-Anzeiger'', 23. July 2004].</ref> ''Junge Lyrik II'' and ''Junge Lyrik III'', a book series published by [[Martin Werhand Verlag]].<ref>''[https://www.martinwerhandverlag.de/buchreihen/junge-lyrik-reihe-750-gedichte-im-mwv/ Junge Lyrik-Reihe: 750 Gedichte].'' [[Martin Werhand Verlag]], 2002</ref> In 2006, he participated in the visual-poetric project ''Poesie bewegt'' of the [[Bremer Stra\u00dfenbahn]] AG under supervision of Joachim Tuz.<ref>[http://www.poesiebewegt.de/liste.html ''Thomas Wensing.'' In: ''Poesie bewegt.'' der [[Bremer Stra\u00dfenbahn]] AG] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904143832/http://www.poesiebewegt.de/liste.html |date=September 4, 2014 }}</ref> Together with the two musicians Martin Schmitz and Michael Wurzel, Wensing formed the trio ''eher selten''<ref>[http://www.ksta.de/region/mal-rockig--mal-sanft,15189102,13711830.html Thomas Wensing in: Mal rockig, mal sanft ''[[K\u00f6lner Stadt-Anzeiger]]'', 22. February 2006]</ref> that performed poetry and music at various occasions in the mid-2000s.<ref>[http://www.ksta.de/region/kein-seelenstriptease,15189102,13485696.html Thomas Wensing in: Kein Seelenstriptease ''[[K\u00f6lner Stadt-Anzeiger]]'', 7. March 2007]</ref> Apart from that group, he tried out his texts in several other formats, e.g. in cooperation with the [[Stadttheater Ingolstadt]].<ref>Thomas Wensing in ''Text und Spiel: Thomas Wensing im Kleinen Haus'', Donaukurier, 7. June 2010</ref>\n\nIn August 2014 [[Martin Werhand Verlag]] published Wensings first own volume of poems (Mitschrift), within the series ''100 Gedichte''.<ref>''[https://www.martinwerhandverlag.de/buchreihen/lyrik-reihe-100-gedichte/ Series: 100 Poems].'' [[Martin Werhand Verlag]], 2016</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=iJ3HoQEACAAJ&dq=Thomas+Wensing&hl=de&sa=X&redir_esc=y ''Mitschrift.'', [[Martin Werhand Verlag]], Melsbach, 2014, 190 Pages]</ref> A volume of short stories (Zwischenspiel) appeared in late 2015 in the same publishing house.<ref>[http://www.martinwerhandverlag.de/publikationen/ ''Thomas Wensing.'' In: ''Martin Werhand Verlag.'', Publikationen 2015]</ref> In December 2019 the MWV published a third book with poems (Herbsttag), within the series ''50 Gedichte''.<ref>''[https://www.martinwerhandverlag.de/buchreihen/lyrik-reihe-50-gedichte-im-mwv/ Lyrik-Reihe: 50 Gedichte].'' [[Martin Werhand Verlag]], 2019</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n=== Monographies ===\n* ''Periodic Review Inventory Systems.'' Performance Analysis and Optimization of Inventory Systems within Supply Chains. Springer, Berlin 2011, 152 p. {{ISBN|978-3-642-20479-1}}.\n* ''Mitschrift.'' 100 Gedichte. Martin Werhand Verlag, Melsbach 2014, 190 p. {{ISBN|978-3-943910-06-3}}.\n* ''Zwischenspiel.'' Kurzgeschichten. Martin Werhand Verlag, Melsbach 2015, 258 p. {{ISBN|978-3-943910-07-0}}.\n* ''Herbsttag.'' 50 Gedichte. Martin Werhand Verlag, Melsbach 2019, 120 p. {{ISBN|978-3-943910-69-8}}.\n\n=== Anthologies ===\n* ''Junge Lyrik \u2013 50 Dichterinnen und Dichter.'' Anthology, Martin Werhand Verlag, Melsbach 1999, {{ISBN|3-9806390-1-0}}.<ref>[http://www.martinwerhandverlag.de/publikationen/ ''Thomas Wensing.'' In: Martin Werhand Verlag]</ref>\n* ''Junge Lyrik II \u2013 50 Dichterinnen und Dichter.'' Anthology, Martin Werhand Verlag, Melsbach 2000, {{ISBN|3-9806390-0-2}}.\n* ''Junge Lyrik III \u2013 50 Dichterinnen und Dichter.'' Anthology, Martin Werhand Verlag, Melsbach 2002, {{ISBN|3-9806390-3-7}}. Also second, revised edition.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=1y6WSgAACAAJ&dq=thorsten+libotte&hl=de&sa=X&ei=YC4GVJCPK-H-4QTAg4CoCw&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAw ''Thomas Wensing.'' In: ''Junge Lyrik: (Jahrg\u00e4nge 1967 \u2013 1982), Band 3.'', Martin Werhand Verlag, Melsbach, 2002, P. 560]</ref>\n\n== Literature (Selection) ==\n* Thomas Wensing in: Frank-Uwe Orbons: ''Die Gedanken gingen auf Wanderschaft'', [[K\u00f6lner Stadt-Anzeiger]], 12. April 2005\n* Thomas Wensing in: Melanie Nicolai: ''Gute Unterhaltung ist ihnen wichtig'', [[K\u00f6lner Stadt-Anzeiger]], 21. February 2006\n* Thomas Wensing in: ''Raffinierte Lyrik und experimentelle Performance'', Donaukurier, 2. April 2006\n* Thomas Wensing in: ''Tradition und Moderne'', Donaukurier, 18. April 2010\n* Thomas Wensing in: ''Aus der Zeitlosigkeit des Kellers'', Donaukurier, 15. June 2010\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Poetry}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.wortgewebe.de/ Official website of Thomas Wensing] {{in lang|de}}\n* {{DNB-Portal|1056029013}}\n* [http://www.nrw-literatur-im-netz.de/datenbank/autoren/1191-wensing-thomas.html Thomas Wensing in: [[NRW Literatur im Netz]]] {{in lang|de}}\n* [https://www.worldcat.org/search?q=au%3AWensing%2C+Thomas&qt=hot_author Thomas Wensing in WorldCat]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wensing, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German-language poets]]\n[[Category:German male poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century German poets]]\n[[Category:Writers from North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:People from Cologne]]\n[[Category:People from the Rhine Province]]\n[[Category:University of Cologne alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Ingolstadt alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century German poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century German male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image = \n| name          = Thomas Wensing\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1978|05|01}}\n| birth_place   = [[Cologne]], [[Germany]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = German\n| othername     = \n| spouse        = \n| yearsactive   = 1999\u2013present\n| occupation    = Writer and poet\n| website       = [http://www.wortgewebe.de/ Official website of Thomas Wensing] {{in lang|de}}\n}}\n'''Thomas Wensing''' (born May 1, 1978 in [[Cologne]]) is a German [[author]] of poetry and short stories.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=_DS3oAEACAAJ&dq=K%C3%BCrschners+Deutscher+Literatur-Kalender+2014&hl=de&sa=X&ei=z9MFVKfjKrKM4gSRuoGgCQ&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAA ''Thomas Wensing.''] In: ''[[K\u00fcrschners Deutscher Literatur-Kalender]] 2014/2015: Band I: A-O. Band II: P-Z.'', Walter De Gruyter Incorporated, 2014, P. 1132, {{ISBN|978-3-11-033720-4}}.</ref>\n\n== Life and works ==\nThomas Wensing, born 1978 in Cologne ([[North Rhine-Westphalia]]) has studied at the [[University of Cologne]] and at the [[Catholic University of Eichst\u00e4tt-Ingolstadt]].<ref>Biographical details of ''Thomas Wensing.'' In: ''Mitschrift.'', Martin Werhand Verlag, 2014, P. 169</ref> He obtained his PhD from the latter institution in 2011.<ref>[http://www.ku.de/wwf/pw/forschung/inventory-management/optimization-of-periodically-reviewed-inventory-systems/ Thomas Wensing at ''Catholic University of Eichst\u00e4tt-Ingolstadt''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150519060254/http://www.ku.de/wwf/pw/forschung/inventory-management/optimization-of-periodically-reviewed-inventory-systems/ |date=May 19, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nBesides studies and occupation, Wensing developed skills in writing literary texts.<ref>Biographical Data of ''Thomas Wensing.'' In: ''Zwischenspiel (Short Stories).'', Martin Werhand Verlag, 2015, P. 233</ref> Since the late 1990s, he has been publishing poetry in a couple of anthologies, e.g. in ''Junge Lyrik'',<ref>[http://www.ksta.de/junge-zeiten/junge-lyrik,16129136,14033596.html ''K\u00f6lner Stadt-Anzeiger'', 23. July 2004].</ref> ''Junge Lyrik II'' and ''Junge Lyrik III'', a book series published by [[Martin Werhand Verlag]].<ref>''[https://www.martinwerhandverlag.de/buchreihen/junge-lyrik-reihe-750-gedichte-im-mwv/ Junge Lyrik-Reihe: 750 Gedichte].'' [[Martin Werhand Verlag]], 2002</ref> In 2006, he participated in the visual-poetric project ''Poesie bewegt'' of the [[Bremer Stra\u00dfenbahn]] AG under supervision of Joachim Tuz.<ref>[http://www.poesiebewegt.de/liste.html ''Thomas Wensing.'' In: ''Poesie bewegt.'' der [[Bremer Stra\u00dfenbahn]] AG] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904143832/http://www.poesiebewegt.de/liste.html |date=September 4, 2014 }}</ref> Together with the two musicians Martin Schmitz and Michael Wurzel, Wensing formed the trio ''eher selten''<ref>[http://www.ksta.de/region/mal-rockig--mal-sanft,15189102,13711830.html Thomas Wensing in: Mal rockig, mal sanft ''[[K\u00f6lner Stadt-Anzeiger]]'', 22. February 2006]</ref> that performed poetry and music at various occasions in the mid-2000s.<ref>[http://www.ksta.de/region/kein-seelenstriptease,15189102,13485696.html Thomas Wensing in: Kein Seelenstriptease ''[[K\u00f6lner Stadt-Anzeiger]]'', 7. March 2007]</ref> Apart from that group, he tried out his texts in several other formats, e.g. in cooperation with the [[Stadttheater Ingolstadt]].<ref>Thomas Wensing in ''Text und Spiel: Thomas Wensing im Kleinen Haus'', Donaukurier, 7. June 2010</ref>\n\nIn August 2014 [[Martin Werhand Verlag]] published Wensings first own volume of poems (Mitschrift), within the series ''100 Gedichte''.<ref>''[https://www.martinwerhandverlag.de/buchreihen/lyrik-reihe-100-gedichte/ Series: 100 Poems].'' [[Martin Werhand Verlag]], 2016</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=iJ3HoQEACAAJ&dq=Thomas+Wensing&hl=de&sa=X&redir_esc=y ''Mitschrift.'', [[Martin Werhand Verlag]], Melsbach, 2014, 190 Pages]</ref> A volume of short stories (Zwischenspiel) appeared in late 2015 in the same publishing house.<ref>[http://www.martinwerhandverlag.de/publikationen/ ''Thomas Wensing.'' In: ''Martin Werhand Verlag.'', Publikationen 2015]</ref> In December 2019 the MWV published a third book with poems (Herbsttag), within the series ''50 Gedichte''.<ref>''[https://www.martinwerhandverlag.de/buchreihen/lyrik-reihe-50-gedichte-im-mwv/ Lyrik-Reihe: 50 Gedichte].'' [[Martin Werhand Verlag]], 2019</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n=== Monographies ===\n* ''Periodic Review Inventory Systems.'' Performance Analysis and Optimization of Inventory Systems within Supply Chains. Springer, Berlin 2011, 152 p. {{ISBN|978-3-642-20479-1}}.\n* ''Mitschrift.'' 100 Gedichte. Martin Werhand Verlag, Melsbach 2014, 190 p. {{ISBN|978-3-943910-06-3}}.\n* ''Zwischenspiel.'' Kurzgeschichten. Martin Werhand Verlag, Melsbach 2015, 258 p. {{ISBN|978-3-943910-07-0}}.\n* ''Herbsttag.'' 50 Gedichte. Martin Werhand Verlag, Melsbach 2019, 120 p. {{ISBN|978-3-943910-69-8}}.\n\n=== Anthologies ===\n* ''Junge Lyrik \u2013 50 Dichterinnen und Dichter.'' Anthology, Martin Werhand Verlag, Melsbach 1999, {{ISBN|3-9806390-1-0}}.<ref>[http://www.martinwerhandverlag.de/publikationen/ ''Thomas Wensing.'' In: Martin Werhand Verlag]</ref>\n* ''Junge Lyrik II \u2013 50 Dichterinnen und Dichter.'' Anthology, Martin Werhand Verlag, Melsbach 2000, {{ISBN|3-9806390-0-2}}.\n* ''Junge Lyrik III \u2013 50 Dichterinnen und Dichter.'' Anthology, Martin Werhand Verlag, Melsbach 2002, {{ISBN|3-9806390-3-7}}. Also second, revised edition.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=1y6WSgAACAAJ&dq=thorsten+libotte&hl=de&sa=X&ei=YC4GVJCPK-H-4QTAg4CoCw&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAw ''Thomas Wensing.'' In: ''Junge Lyrik: (Jahrg\u00e4nge 1967 \u2013 1982), Band 3.'', Martin Werhand Verlag, Melsbach, 2002, P. 560]</ref>\n\n== Literature (Selection) ==\n* Thomas Wensing in: Frank-Uwe Orbons: ''Die Gedanken gingen auf Wanderschaft'', [[K\u00f6lner Stadt-Anzeiger]], 12. April 2005\n* Thomas Wensing in: Melanie Nicolai: ''Gute Unterhaltung ist ihnen wichtig'', [[K\u00f6lner Stadt-Anzeiger]], 21. February 2006\n* Thomas Wensing in: ''Raffinierte Lyrik und experimentelle Performance'', Donaukurier, 2. April 2006\n* Thomas Wensing in: ''Tradition und Moderne'', Donaukurier, 18. April 2010\n* Thomas Wensing in: ''Aus der Zeitlosigkeit des Kellers'', Donaukurier, 15. June 2010\n\n==See 